{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a31426c4ddea681e", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tAn Efficient vLLM-Based Inference Pipeline for Unified Audio Understanding\n2\tand Generation\n3\tHaoran Wang1,2 , Jinchuan Tian1 , Siddhant Arora1 , Shinji Watanabe1,∗∗\n4\t1\n5\t2\n6\t\n7\tCarnegie Mellon University\n8\tShanghai Jiao Tong University\n9\thaoranw5@andrew.cmu.edu\n10\t\n11\tarXiv:2607.02119v1 [eess.AS] 2 Jul 2026\n12\t\n13\tAbstract\n14\tWhile Large Multimodal Models excel in comprehension, highthroughput inference engines lack native support for multimodal generation. This is severe in Speech Language Models, where generating multi-layered audio tokens via decoupled\n15\tAR+NAR or synchronous Multi-Token Prediction (MTP) with\n16\tdelay-pattern interleaving conflicts with standard single-stream\n17\tloops. We present a vLLM-based inference pipeline for unified\n18\tspeech understanding and generation. We extend autoregressive decoding to natively execute delay-pattern de-interleaving\n19\tand coordinated multi-stream sampling, integrating an on-GPU\n20\tacoustic decoder for end-to-end waveform synthesis. Crucially,\n21\twe overcome the shared intuition that Classifier-Free Guidance\n22\t(CFG) halves throughput. By co-scheduling paired conditional\n23\tand unconditional requests within a continuous batch, our CFG\n24\timplementation sustains 80% of non-CFG throughput, absorbing dual-request and logit merging overheads. We open-source\n25\tour framework1 .\n26\tIndex Terms: Speech Language Models, High-Throughput Inference, End-to-End Speech Generation\n27\t\n28\t1. Introduction\n29\tThe rapid evolution of Large Language Models (LLMs) has\n30\ttransitioned artificial intelligence from text-only interfaces to\n31\trich, multimodal interactions. Recently, Speech Language\n32\tModels (SpeechLMs) [1, 2, 3, 4] have emerged as a pivotal frontier for unified audio understanding and generation.\n33\tBy modeling continuous audio signals as discrete acoustic tokens [5, 6, 7], these models bypass traditional cascaded Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) [8] and Text-to-Speech\n34\t(TTS) [9, 10] pipelines to achieve strong and expressive acoustic capabilities. Building upon this end-to-end foundation, advanced interactive features like direct speech-to-speech dialogue [11, 12] naturally emerge as downstream applications.\n35\tHowever, the deployment of SpeechLMs exposes a structural gap in current high-throughput inference engines. While\n36\tstate-of-the-art serving frameworks [13, 14] excel at memory\n37\tefficiency and dynamic request scheduling (e.g., continuous\n38\tbatching [15] and automatic prefix caching [14]), their underlying mechanisms were largely optimized for unimodal, text-only\n39\tgeneration. Consequently, extending this text-centric architecture to handle the continuous and distinct nature of speech outputs introduces significant bottlenecks.\n40\tGenerating general audio diverges from standard text autoregression in two critical aspects:\n41\t** indicates the corresponding author.\n42\t1 https://github.com/whr-a/vllm/tree/opuslm\n43\t\n44\t1. Multi-Layered Token Generation and Decoding. Unlike\n45\ttext, continuous speech is typically compressed by neural audio codecs [5, 7, 16, 17]. Modern SpeechLMs favor Residual\n46\tVector Quantization (RVQ), encoding each temporal frame\n47\tinto multi-layered tokens to support high-fidelity audio at\n48\ta constant frame rate. To model this multi-codebook grid,\n49\tcurrent paradigms primarily adopt synchronous Multi-Token\n50\tPrediction (MTP) [3] and delay-pattern interleaving [1, 18].\n51\tWhile delay-pattern elegantly flattens tokens for training, its\n52\tinference demands multi-stream sampling and complex deinterleaving. Furthermore, synthesizing the final waveform\n53\trequires an auxiliary acoustic decoder (vocoder). Coupling\n54\tMTP with this additional decoding stage inherently conflicts\n55\twith the standard one-token-per-step serving loop.\n56\t2. The Classifier-Free Guidance (CFG) Bottleneck.\n57\tClassifier-Free Guidance (CFG) [19] is essential for highfidelity audio generation, as evidenced by its widespread\n58\tadoption in various audio synthesis frameworks [18, 20, 21].\n59\tMechanistically, implementing CFG requires two parallel\n60\tforward passes per step: one conditioned on the input\n61\tprompt and one unconditional. This dual-pass requirement\n62\tinherently doubles computational and memory overheads.\n63\tSince standard schedulers assume strict request independence, they lack native mechanisms to coordinate these\n64\tpaired passes. Consequently, naive implementations are\n65\tforced to process them as separate requests. This disjoint\n66\tscheduling duplicates KV cache allocations and precludes\n67\tjoint batching. Furthermore, the necessary logit merging\n68\tmust operate across disjoint request contexts with explicit\n69\tsynchronization. The compounding of these dual-request\n70\toverheads and synchronization costs can severely degrade\n71\toverall system throughput.\n72\tTo bridge this gap, we present a novel inference implementation engineered for the unified understanding and generation\n73\tof audio. Built upon vLLM [13] which is a high-performance\n74\tcontinuous batching backend, our framework extends the autoregressive decoding loop to natively support synchronous\n75\tmulti-stream sampling with delay-pattern de-interleaving for\n76\tmulti-codebook audio generation. Furthermore, we fuse a\n77\tlightweight acoustic decoder directly into the engine’s output\n78\tpipeline, enabling single-process audio synthesis without an external vocoder service\n79\tTo address the CFG overhead, we introduce a Paired Request Co-Scheduling mechanism. By co-scheduling paired conditional and unconditional requests within the same continuous\n80\tbatch, our approach ensures them to share a single forward pass\n81\tthrough the transformer backbone. This unified execution elegantly absorbs the dual-request and logits merging overheads,\n82\tdirectly overcoming the shared intuition that CFG inevitably\n83\thalves system throughput.\n84\t\n85\t\fCodebook token prediction head\n86\t\n87\tDelay Pattern\n88\t-ccccc\n89\t--cccc\n90\t\n91\t...\n92\t\n93\t...\n94\t\n95\t-----c\n96\tDe-interleave\n97\tAcoustic\n98\tDecoder\n99\t\n100\tLLM Model Backbone\n101\t\n102\tAudio Encoder\n103\t\n104\tText Input\n105\tText Output\n106\tAudio Output\n107\t\n108\tAudio Input\n109\t\n110\tFigure 1: Speech language model architecture. The unified\n111\tautoregressive transformer processes encoded audio and text.\n112\tDuring audio generation, hidden states ht and stream embeddings ei (where 1 ≤ i ≤ S) are projected via S codebook\n113\theads into parallel delayed streams, which are subsequently deinterleaved for acoustic decoding.\n114\tThe main contributions are summarized as follows.\n115\t1. We identify the structural limitations of current text-centric\n116\tinference engines in handling multimodal auto-regressive\n117\tgeneration and propose a unified architecture that natively\n118\tsupports synchronous multi-stream sampling and delaypattern de-interleaving for multi-codebook audio tokens.\n119\t2. We design an end-to-end fused acoustic pipeline that integrates a lightweight audio decoder directly into the engine’s\n120\toutput pipeline, eliminating the need for an external vocoder\n121\tservice and enabling single-process waveform synthesis on\n122\tGPU.\n123\t3. We introduce a Paired Request Co-Scheduling strategy for\n124\tCFG. By systematically pairing and co-scheduling conditional and unconditional requests within the same continuous\n125\tbatch, our system efficiently absorbs dual-branch overheads\n126\tand logit synchronization costs, sustaining up to 80% of nonCFG throughput and effectively overcoming the shared intuition of halved performance, while seamlessly supporting the\n127\tconcurrent prefilling and decoding of text and CFG-enabled\n128\taudio requests in a unified pipeline.\n129\t\n130\t2. Method\n131\tWe present a serving framework that enables high-throughput\n132\tinference for unified audio understanding and generation within\n133\texisting token-level continuous batching engines. We first describe the class of models our framework targets (§2.1), then\n134\tdetail our unified serving pipeline (§2.3), and finally describe\n135\tefficient Classifier-Free Guidance (§2.4).\n136\t2.1. Speech Language Models\n137\tOur system broadly targets the widely adopted delaypattern [18] SpeechLM architecture. To validate the generality\n138\tof our pipeline, we ground our implementation and evaluation\n139\tin three representative models: Bagpiper [1], OpusLM [2], and\n140\tOpusLM dialogue [11]. As illustrated in Figure 1, the core generation mechanisms of these models share a unified architec-\n141\t\n142\ttural foundation.\n143\tMulti-token Prediction. The pipeline begins with an audio\n144\tencoder feeding continuous speech to an autoregressive LLM.\n145\tThe LLM operates over a unified vocabulary, partitioned into\n146\ttext and S audio sub-vocabulary. For audio output, at each time\n147\tstep t, the LLM backbone produces a hidden state ht . As illustrated in Figure 1, S parallel codebook heads then project this\n148\tstate to generate logits ℓ(i) and their corresponding sampled tokens ci (where 1 ≤ i ≤ S). Specifically, each head adds a\n149\tlearnable stream embedding ei to ht before applying a shared\n150\tlanguage modeling head WH , such that ℓ(i) = WH (ht + ei ).\n151\tDelay Interleave pattern. Under the delay pattern [18],\n152\tthe i-th stream is offset by i steps, meaning the S tokens\n153\t{c1 , . . . , cS } emitted at step t correspond to different temporal\n154\tpositions. To maintain this structure during autoregressive feedback, the input representation at each step aggregates the embeddings of these previously generated tokens. Post-generation,\n155\tthe resulting S × T codebook matrix (where T represents the\n156\ttotal number of acoustic frames) is de-interleaved and passed to\n157\tan acoustic decoder for waveform synthesis. Crucially, this unified vocabulary inherently enables mixed-modality responses\n158\t(e.g., text seamlessly transitioning to audio).\n159\t2.2. Standard Continuous Batching Engines\n160\tModern text-based LLM serving frameworks, such as\n161\tvLLM [13], maximize hardware utilization through iterationlevel scheduling and continuous batching. Rather than processing static batches where early-finishing requests idle, the\n162\tscheduler dynamically injects new prompts and retires completed generations at the granularity of a single decoding step.\n163\tThis highly dynamic scheduling is supported by memory management mechanisms like PagedAttention [13], which partitions the Key-Value (KV) cache into fixed-size, non-contiguous\n164\tblocks to allocate GPU memory on demand and eliminate fragmentation. Structurally, these engines treat the underlying\n165\tmodel as a black box that executes a uniform forward pass\n166\tacross all active requests. Consequently, the entire system infrastructure is deeply coupled to the assumption of homogeneous, single-stream text generation, presenting a strict architectural constraint that our framework must navigate to support\n167\tmulti-token prediction and CFG inference.\n168\t2.3. Unified Multi-Token Prediction Serving Pipeline\n169\tTo navigate this single-stream constraint and support S parallel audio tokens without requiring pervasive modifications to\n170\tthe engine’s iteration-level scheduler or PagedAttention [13] infrastructure, we introduce a primary-auxiliary decomposition,\n171\tas depicted in Figure 2 (Left).\n172\tPrimary-Auxiliary Decomposition. We designate one\n173\tcodebook stream as the primary token, which is fully managed\n174\tby the engine’s standard pipeline. The remaining S−1 auxiliary\n175\tstreams are sampled internally during the model’s logit computation and buffered per-request. Consequently, the model appears to the engine as a standard text LM that emits a single token per step, while transparently executing the multi-codebook\n176\tgeneration.\n177\tDe-interleave and Decode. Upon request completion, the\n178\tbuffered matrix is delay-de-interleaved and passed to a colocated on-GPU acoustic decoder, fusing waveform synthesis\n179\tdirectly into the serving path.\n180\tMixed-Modality Phase Management. To orchestrate\n181\tmixed text-audio outputs within this token-level engine, we implement a per-request phase state machine enforced via dy-\n182\t\n183\t\fText and/or\n184\tRaw Audio\n185\t\n186\tRequest\n187\t(CFG>1)\n188\tauto-allocate\n189\t\n190\tServer\n191\tScheduler\n192\tMain\n193\t(w/ cond)\n194\t\n195\tCompanion\n196\t(w/o cond)\n197\t\n198\tModel\n199\ttext\n200\t\n201\taudio\n202\tDe-interleave\n203\t\n204\tAudio\n205\tDecoder\n206\t\n207\tShared Forward\n208\t(scheduled in the same batch)\n209\t\n210\tCFG Merge\n211\tsample\n212\t\n213\tAssistant\n214\tMessage\n215\t\n216\tMain Token\n217\t\n218\tCompanion\n219\tSync Token\n220\t\n221\tNext step\n222\t\n223\tFigure 2: Unified serving framework for SpeechLMs. (Left)\n224\tOverall pipeline: The engine manages continuous batching,\n225\tprimary-auxiliary token generation, and fused on-GPU acoustic decoding for mixed-modality streaming. (Right) Paired coscheduling for CFG: Conditional and unconditional requests\n226\tshare a batched forward pass, merging logits before sampling\n227\tand synchronizing the sampled token for the next step.\n228\tnamic vocabulary masking. The system transitions across three\n229\tmain states: a text phase restricted to text tokens, a transition\n230\tphase injecting deterministic bridging tokens to condition audio\n231\tgeneration, and an audio phase activating all S streams. Crucially, terminating the audio phase initiates a drain sub-phase\n232\tthat emits S−1 padding tokens to flush the delay buffer, guaranteeing a complete S × T codebook matrix (where T represents the total number of acoustic frames) for de-interleaving.\n233\tFurthermore, because continuous batching interleaves tokens\n234\tfrom multiple requests into a single flattened sequence, tracking modality via input positions is unreliable. We bypass this\n235\tby dynamically inferring the active modality directly from the\n236\tmodel’s unmasked output distribution (i.e., the argmax over\n237\tthe disjoint vocabulary regions), ensuring robust and engineagnostic phase management.\n238\t2.4. Classifier-Free Guidance via Paired Request CoScheduling\n239\tClassifier-Free Guidance (CFG) [19] improves audio fidelity by\n240\tinterpolating between conditional and unconditional distributions. Building upon the logit formulation ℓ(i) defined in Section 2.3, we apply CFG independently to each codebook stream\n241\ti:\n242\t(i)\n243\t(i)\n244\tℓ̃(i) = w · ℓcond + (1 − w) · ℓuncond , w > 1\n245\t(1)\n246\tA straightforward implementation would issue two independent requests, incurring severe scheduling fragmentation and\n247\tcross-request synchronization overhead, and is not feasible because it needs step-by-step sync. To resolve this, we introduce\n248\tpaired request co-scheduling, which natively coordinates this\n249\tdual-pass requirement within the serving engine.\n250\tAs detailed in Figure 2 (Right), the end-to-end processing\n251\tpipeline begins with the input auto-allocation: when the server\n252\treceives a request with a CFG scale w > 1, it transparently generates a “Companion” request (with a null prompt) alongside\n253\tthe “Main” conditional request. The engine treats this pair as an\n254\tatomic scheduling unit and always process them together. During the shared forward process, they are co-scheduled into the\n255\t\n256\tsame continuous batch and share a single forward pass through\n257\tthe transformer backbone. The engine strictly partitions the perstep token budget equally between the pair.\n258\t(i)\n259\t(i)\n260\tAfter the forward pass, the raw logits ℓcond and ℓuncond from\n261\tboth contexts are merged according to Eq. 1. Crucially, this\n262\tCFG merge operates only during the audio phase; it bypasses\n263\tmodality-switching tokens to prevent CFG from corrupting the\n264\tphase state machine. To avoid redundant compute, projections\n265\tfor auxiliary streams are batched together.\n266\tFinally, for the output and synchronization step, the engine\n267\tsamples a single Main Token from the merged distribution ℓ̃(i) .\n268\tTo ensure both contexts maintain the exact same autoregressive\n269\thistory for the next step, this sampled token is synchronously\n270\tappended to the Companion request, while the companion’s external outputs remain hidden from the client. By systematically\n271\tco-scheduling these pairs within the same continuous batch, our\n272\tarchitecture efficiently absorbs the dual-branch overheads and\n273\tlogit synchronization costs. This design effectively overcomes\n274\tthe conventional assumption that CFG halves performance, allowing the system to sustain up to 80% of non-CFG throughput.\n275\t\n276\t3. Experiment\n277\t3.1. Experimental Setup\n278\tWe evaluate our framework on three fully open-source\n279\tSpeechLM architectures that span different design points, all\n280\tsharing a delay-pattern codec structure and supporting both audio understanding and generation:\n281\t• Bagpiper [1]: A model utilizing a Qwen3-8B [22] backbone\n282\twith 8 parallel codebook streams encoded via X-Codec [6].\n283\tIt is designed for open-ended audio understanding and generation, natively supporting Classifier-Free Guidance for highfidelity audio synthesis.\n284\t• OpusLM [2]: A model featuring an OLMo-2-7B [23] backbone with a 9-stream setup (1 SSL [24] + 8 DAC [5, 25]),\n285\ttailored for both ASR and TTS tasks.\n286\t• OpusLM-Dialogue [11]: A model adopting a SmolLM21.7B [26] backbone. It retains the same 9-stream codec configuration as OpusLM but is specifically optimized for spoken\n287\tdialogue tasks.\n288\tFor the baseline, we use the original PyTorch inference\n289\tpipeline, which processes requests sequentially without continuous batching. All experiments are conducted on a single\n290\tNVIDIA H100 80GB GPU with FlashAttention-3 [27] enabled.\n291\tThe maximum model sequence length is set to 16,384 tokens for\n292\tall configurations. To maximize operational efficiency and fully\n293\tsaturate the GPU, we maintain a concurrency level of 512 simultaneous requests for standard evaluations. For CFG-enabled\n294\tsettings, the concurrency is proportionally adjusted to 256 requests to account for the internal companion requests, yielding an equivalent active workload. This targeted concurrency\n295\tensures that the serving engine maintains a steady, moderately\n296\tsized queue to sustain peak overall throughput.\n297\t3.2. Throughput\n298\tIn addition to decode token rates, we measure Model FLOPs\n299\tUtilization (MFU), which quantifies the ratio of actual floatingpoint operations to the GPU’s theoretical peak capacity, providing a standardized metric for hardware utility. As summarized in Table 1, our continuous-batching pipeline achieves\n300\tmassive performance gains over the sequential PyTorch baseline across all models. By effectively batching multi-stream\n301\tgeneration, our system accelerates token processing speeds by\n302\t\n303\t\fTable 1: Prompt and generation throughput comparison. All\n304\tmeasurements are conducted on a single H100 80GB GPU with\n305\tFlashAttention-3 and a maximum sequence length of 16,384.\n306\tSystem\n307\t\n308\tDecode (tok/s) MFU (%)\n309\t\n310\tBagpiper (PyTorch)\n311\tBagpiper (vLLM)\n312\t\n313\t52.7\n314\t5694.5\n315\t\n316\tTable 3: Inference quality evaluation. Understanding is measured by MMAU-mini accuracy (%, ↑) and ASR word error rate\n317\t(%, ↓). Generation is measured by TTS word error rate (%, ↓)\n318\tand dialogue UTMOS (↑). “–” indicates the task is not supported by the model.\n319\t\n320\t0.096\n321\t9.95\n322\t\n323\tUnderstanding\n324\tMMAU↑\n325\t-mini\n326\t\n327\tASR↓\n328\t\n329\tTTS↓\n330\t\n331\tUTMOS↑\n332\t\n333\tBagpiper (PyTorch)\n334\tBagpiper (vLLM)\n335\t\n336\t74.5\n337\t75.4\n338\t\n339\t2.5\n340\t2.6\n341\t\n342\t2.7\n343\t3.3\n344\t\n345\t–\n346\t–\n347\t\n348\tOpusLM (PyTorch)\n349\tOpusLM (vLLM)\n350\t\n351\t–\n352\t–\n353\t\n354\t2.3\n355\t1.9\n356\t\n357\t4.6\n358\t5.3\n359\t\n360\t–\n361\t–\n362\t\n363\tOpusLM-Dial. (PyTorch)\n364\tOpusLM-Dial. (vLLM)\n365\t\n366\t–\n367\t–\n368\t\n369\t–\n370\t–\n371\t\n372\t–\n373\t–\n374\t\n375\t2.85\n376\t2.51\n377\t\n378\tOpusLM (PyTorch)\n379\tOpusLM (vLLM)\n380\t\n381\t36.5\n382\t4582.9\n383\t\n384\t0.311\n385\t9.89\n386\t\n387\tOpusLM-Dial. (PyTorch)\n388\tOpusLM-Dial. (vLLM)\n389\t\n390\t53.9\n391\t5870.5\n392\t\n393\t0.290\n394\t3.28\n395\t\n396\troughly two orders of magnitude. This architectural advantage\n397\tdirectly translates to hardware utilization: while the baseline\n398\tseverely underutilizes the H100 GPU with an MFU well below\n399\t0.1%, our serving engine efficiently absorbs scheduling overheads to drive the MFU up to 9.95% for Bagpiper and 9.89%\n400\tfor OpusLM. Notably, the 1.7B parameter OpusLM dialogue\n401\tmodel exhibits a lower MFU of 3.28% despite achieving the\n402\thighest absolute token throughput. This occurs because such a\n403\tcompact model possesses low arithmetic intensity on the H100\n404\tGPU, causing inference to hit the memory bandwidth wall before fully saturating the compute units.\n405\t3.3. Numerical and Quality Check\n406\tA prerequisite for any serving optimization is that it must not\n407\tdegrade model output quality. We verify numerical correctness\n408\tusing the Bagpiper model [1] on the MMAU-mini dataset [28].\n409\tSpecifically, we compare the token sequences and logit distributions produced by our continuous-batching pipeline against the\n410\treference PyTorch implementation under identical inputs and\n411\trandom seeds.\n412\tTable 2: Numerical deviation against the reference PyTorch implementation.\n413\tConfiguration\n414\t\n415\tRMSE\n416\t(Max)\n417\t\n418\tRMSE\n419\t(Mean)\n420\t\n421\tFirst\n422\tMismatch\n423\t\n424\tFP32 + SDPA [29]\n425\tBF16 + FA3 [27]\n426\t\n427\t0.081\n428\t0.532\n429\t\n430\t0.008\n431\t0.163\n432\t\n433\tNone (Identical)\n434\t34.0\n435\t\n436\tAs shown in Table 2, under Float32 precision, the two implementations produce strictly identical token sequences, with\n437\ta negligible mean logit RMSE of 0.008. This exact alignment\n438\tconfirms that our custom multi-stream sampling and phase control introduce no numerical bugs. When transitioning to BF16\n439\twith FlashAttention-3 [27], a mismatch occurs around step\n440\t34, increasing the mean RMSE to 0.163. This discrepancy is\n441\tan expected consequence of precision loss and non-associative\n442\tfloating-point arithmetic [30, 31].\n443\tCrucially, this inherent hardware-level divergence does not\n444\tnegatively impact end-to-end model fidelity. To confirm this\n445\tempirically, we evaluate inference quality across understanding and generation tasks, as summarized in Table 3. We report\n446\taccuracy on MMAU-mini [28] and word error rate (WER) on\n447\tLibriSpeech test-clean [32] for understanding. For generation,\n448\twe report WER on LibriSpeech test-clean and UTMOS on the\n449\tEval2000 dataset. While minor instance-level variations in synthesized speech naturally arise from hardware precision shifts\n450\tand the inherent variance of TTS generation, outputs produced\n451\tby our pipeline safely maintain the expected aggregate performance of the underlying models across all metrics.\n452\t\n453\tSystem\n454\t\n455\tGeneration\n456\t\n457\tTable 4: CFG overhead on Bagpiper (vLLM). Prompt and\n458\tgeneration throughput (tok/s) and MFU (%) with and without\n459\tClassifier-Free Guidance.\n460\tSetting\n461\t\n462\tPrefill (tok/s)\n463\t\n464\tDecode (tok/s)\n465\t\n466\tMFU (%)\n467\t\n468\tw/o CFG\n469\tw/ CFG\n470\t\n471\t315.8\n472\t271.2\n473\t\n474\t4952.0\n475\t3960.7\n476\t\n477\t8.0\n478\t12.8\n479\t\n480\t3.4. CFG Overhead Analysis\n481\tWhile CFG inherently doubles compute via parallel forward\n482\tpasses, Table 4 shows our co-scheduling sustains over 80% of\n483\tbaseline throughput. These measurements are conducted using\n484\tBagpiper on the LibriSpeech TTS task, operating at concurrencies of 256 and 512 for the CFG and baseline configurations,\n485\trespectively. This efficiency stems from three factors. First,\n486\tthe companion request strictly copies the main sequence, ensuring near-perfect prefix cache hits and minimizing KV cache\n487\toverhead. Second, since autoregressive decoding is fundamentally memory-bound, processing the companion request merely\n488\tconstitutes a marginal addition to the active batch size. This\n489\tsaturates idle compute to boost MFU with negligible latency\n490\tand synchronization penalties. Finally, models like Bagpiper\n491\tgenerate extensive textual reasoning before brief audio outputs.\n492\tSelectively activating CFG solely during this short audio phase\n493\teffectively amortizes the dual-pass cost across the entire end-toend sequence.\n494\t\n495\t4. Conclusion\n496\tIn this work, we presented a unified inference architecture\n497\tthat extends a continuous batching engine to natively support\n498\tSpeech Language Models. By integrating synchronous multistream sampling and delay-pattern de-interleaving into the generation loop, our design effectively handles the complexities\n499\tof multi-layered audio tokens. Through a Paired Request CoScheduling strategy, our system efficiently absorbs dual-branch\n500\toverheads, sustaining 80% of non-CFG throughput. Experimental results across multiple SpeechLM architectures demonstrate up to 108× generation throughput improvement over sequential PyTorch inference while maintaining strict numerical correctness. As the modifications remain confined to the\n501\tmodel and logit processing layers, this architecture provides a\n502\tportable and high-performance foundation for real-time multimodal voice applications.\n503\t\n504\t\f5. Generative AI Use Disclosure\n505\tArtificial intelligence tools were utilized exclusively for language editing and manuscript polishing. The core technical\n506\tcontributions, including the system architecture design, framework implementation, and experimental evaluation, were independently conducted by the authors.\n507\t\n508\t6. Acknowledgment\n509\tThis work used the Bridges2 at PSC and Delta/DeltaAI NCSA\n510\tsystems through CIS210014 from the ACCESS program, supported by NSF #2138259, #2138286, #2138307, #2137603, and\n511\t#2138296.\n512\t\n513\t7. References\n514\t[1] J. Tian, H. Wang, B.-H. Su, C.-y. Huang, Q. Wang, J. Shi,\n515\tW. Chen, X. Gong, S. Arora, C.-J. Li et al., “Bagpiper: Solving open-ended audio tasks via rich captions,” arXiv preprint\n516\tarXiv:2602.05220, 2026.\n517\t[2] J. Tian, W. Chen, Y. Peng, J. Shi, S. Arora, S. Bharadwaj,\n518\tT. Maekaku, Y. Shinohara, K. Goto, X. Yue et al., “Opuslm: A\n519\tfamily of open unified speech language models,” arXiv preprint\n520\tarXiv:2506.17611, 2025.\n521\t[3] J. Xu, Z. Guo, H. Hu, Y. Chu, X. Wang, J. He, Y. Wang,\n522\tX. Shi, T. He, X. Zhu et al., “Qwen3-omni technical report,” arXiv\n523\tpreprint arXiv:2509.17765, 2025.\n524\t[4] D. Ding, Z. Ju, Y. Leng, S. Liu, T. Liu, Z. Shang, K. Shen,\n525\tW. Song, X. Tan, H. Tang et al., “Kimi-audio technical report,”\n526\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2504.18425, 2025.\n527\t[5] J. Shi, J. Tian, Y. Wu, J.-w. Jung, J. Q. Yip, Y. Masuyama,\n528\tW. Chen, Y. Wu, Y. Tang, M. Baali et al., “Espnet-codec: Comprehensive training and evaluation of neural codecs for audio, music,\n529\tand speech,” in 2024 IEEE Spoken language technology workshop\n530\t(SLT). IEEE, 2024, pp. 562–569.\n531\t[6] Z. Ye, P. Sun, J. Lei, H. Lin, X. Tan, Z. Dai, Q. Kong, J. Chen,\n532\tJ. Pan, Q. Liu et al., “Codec does matter: Exploring the semantic\n533\tshortcoming of codec for audio language model,” in Proceedings\n534\tof the AAAI Conference on Artificial Intelligence, vol. 39, no. 24,\n535\t2025, pp. 25 697–25 705.\n536\t[7] H. Wang, J. Shi, J. Tian, B. Li, K. Yu, and S. Watanabe, “Bscodec:\n537\tA band-split neural codec for high-quality universal audio reconstruction,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2511.06150, 2025.\n538\t[8] A. Radford, J. W. Kim, T. Xu, G. Brockman, C. McLeavey, and\n539\tI. Sutskever, “Robust speech recognition via large-scale weak\n540\tsupervision,” in International conference on machine learning.\n541\tPMLR, 2023, pp. 28 492–28 518.\n542\t\n543\t[13] W. Kwon, Z. Li, S. Zhuang, Y. Sheng, L. Zheng, C. H. Yu, J. E.\n544\tGonzalez, H. Zhang, and I. Stoica, “Efficient memory management for large language model serving with pagedattention,” in\n545\tProceedings of the ACM SIGOPS 29th Symposium on Operating\n546\tSystems Principles, 2023.\n547\t[14] L. Zheng, L. Yin, Z. Xie, C. L. Sun, J. Huang, C. H. Yu, S. Cao,\n548\tC. Kozyrakis, I. Stoica, J. E. Gonzalez et al., “Sglang: Efficient\n549\texecution of structured language model programs,” Advances\n550\tin neural information processing systems, vol. 37, pp. 62 557–\n551\t62 583, 2024.\n552\t[15] G.-I. Yu, J. S. Jeong, G.-W. Kim, S. Kim, and B.-G. Chun, “Orca:\n553\tA distributed serving system for {Transformer-Based} generative\n554\tmodels,” in 16th USENIX symposium on operating systems design\n555\tand implementation (OSDI 22), 2022, pp. 521–538.\n556\t[16] P. Mousavi, G. Maimon, A. Moumen, D. Petermann, J. Shi,\n557\tH. Wu, H. Yang, A. Kuznetsova, A. Ploujnikov, R. Marxer et al.,\n558\t“Discrete audio tokens: More than a survey!” arXiv preprint\n559\tarXiv:2506.10274, 2025.\n560\t[17] Y. Guo, Z. Li, H. Wang, B. Li, C. Shao, H. Zhang, C. Du, X. Chen,\n561\tS. Liu, and K. Yu, “Recent advances in discrete speech tokens:\n562\tA review,” IEEE Transactions on Pattern Analysis and Machine\n563\tIntelligence, 2025.\n564\t[18] J. Copet, F. Kreuk, I. Gat, T. Remez, D. Kant, G. Synnaeve,\n565\tY. Adi, and A. Défossez, “Simple and controllable music generation,” Advances in neural information processing systems, vol. 36,\n566\tpp. 47 704–47 720, 2023.\n567\t[19] J. Ho and T. Salimans, “Classifier-free diffusion guidance,” arXiv\n568\tpreprint arXiv:2207.12598, 2022.\n569\t[20] J. Tian, S.-g. Lee, Z. Kong, S. Ghosh, A. Goel, C.-H. H. Yang,\n570\tW. Dai, Z. Liu, H. Ye, S. Watanabe et al., “Ualm: Unified audio language model for understanding, generation and reasoning,”\n571\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2510.12000, 2025.\n572\t[21] H. Liu, Z. Chen, Y. Yuan, X. Mei, X. Liu, D. Mandic, W. Wang,\n573\tand M. D. Plumbley, “Audioldm: Text-to-audio generation with\n574\tlatent diffusion models,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2301.12503, 2023.\n575\t[22] A. Yang, A. Li, B. Yang, B. Zhang, B. Hui, B. Zheng, B. Yu,\n576\tC. Gao, C. Huang, C. Lv et al., “Qwen3 technical report,” arXiv\n577\tpreprint arXiv:2505.09388, 2025.\n578\t[23] T. OLMo, P. Walsh, L. Soldaini, D. Groeneveld, K. Lo, S. Arora,\n579\tA. Bhagia, Y. Gu, S. Huang, M. Jordan et al., “2 olmo 2 furious,”\n580\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2501.00656, 2024.\n581\t[24] W. Chen, W. Zhang, Y. Peng, X. Li, J. Tian, J. Shi, X. Chang,\n582\tS. Maiti, K. Livescu, and S. Watanabe, “Towards robust speech\n583\trepresentation learning for thousands of languages,” in Proceedings of the 2024 Conference on Empirical Methods in Natural\n584\tLanguage Processing, 2024, pp. 10 205–10 224.\n585\t[25] R. Kumar, P. Seetharaman, A. Luebs, I. Kumar, and K. Kumar,\n586\t“High-fidelity audio compression with improved rvqgan,” Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems, vol. 36, pp.\n587\t27 980–27 993, 2023.\n588\t\n589\t[9] J. Kim, J. Kong, and J. Son, “Conditional variational autoencoder\n590\twith adversarial learning for end-to-end text-to-speech,” in International conference on machine learning.\n591\tPMLR, 2021, pp.\n592\t5530–5540.\n593\t\n594\t[26] L. B. Allal, A. Lozhkov, E. Bakouch, G. M. Blázquez, G. Penedo,\n595\tL. Tunstall, A. Marafioti, H. Kydlı́ček, A. P. Lajarı́n, V. Srivastav\n596\tet al., “Smollm2: When smol goes big–data-centric training of a\n597\tsmall language model,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2502.02737, 2025.\n598\t\n599\t[10] J. Shen, R. Pang, R. J. Weiss, M. Schuster, N. Jaitly, Z. Yang,\n600\tZ. Chen, Y. Zhang, Y. Wang, R. Skerrv-Ryan et al., “Natural\n601\ttts synthesis by conditioning wavenet on mel spectrogram predictions,” in 2018 IEEE international conference on acoustics,\n602\tspeech and signal processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2018, pp. 4779–\n603\t4783.\n604\t\n605\t[27] J. Shah, G. Bikshandi, Y. Zhang, V. Thakkar, P. Ramani, and\n606\tT. Dao, “Flashattention-3: Fast and accurate attention with asynchrony and low-precision,” Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems, vol. 37, pp. 68 658–68 685, 2024.\n607\t\n608\t[11] S. Arora, J. Tian, J. Shi, H. Futami, Y. Kashiwagi, E. Tsunoo,\n609\tand S. Watanabe, “Optimizing conversational quality in spoken\n610\tdialogue systems with reinforcement learning from ai feedback,”\n611\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2601.19063, 2026.\n612\t[12] A. Défossez, L. Mazaré, M. Orsini, A. Royer, P. Pérez, H. Jégou,\n613\tE. Grave, and N. Zeghidour, “Moshi: a speech-text foundation\n614\tmodel for real-time dialogue,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2410.00037,\n615\t2024.\n616\t\n617\t[28] S. Sakshi, U. Tyagi, S. Kumar, A. Seth, R. Selvakumar, O. Nieto,\n618\tR. Duraiswami, S. Ghosh, and D. Manocha, “Mmau: A massive\n619\tmulti-task audio understanding and reasoning benchmark,” arXiv\n620\tpreprint arXiv:2410.19168, 2024.\n621\t[29] A. Vaswani, N. Shazeer, N. Parmar, J. Uszkoreit, L. Jones, A. N.\n622\tGomez, Ł. Kaiser, and I. Polosukhin, “Attention is all you need,”\n623\tAdvances in neural information processing systems, vol. 30, 2017.\n624\t[30] A. Golden, S. Hsia, F. Sun, B. Acun, B. Hosmer, Y. Lee, Z. DeVito, J. Johnson, G.-Y. Wei, D. Brooks et al., “Is flash attention\n625\tstable?” arXiv preprint arXiv:2405.02803, 2024.\n626\t\n627\t\f[31] J. Yuan, H. Li, X. Ding, W. Xie, Y.-J. Li, W. Zhao, K. Wan,\n628\tJ. Shi, X. Hu, and Z. Liu, “Understanding and mitigating numerical sources of nondeterminism in llm inference,” arXiv preprint\n629\tarXiv:2506.09501, 2025.\n630\t[32] V. Panayotov, G. Chen, D. Povey, and S. Khudanpur, “Librispeech: an asr corpus based on public domain audio books,”\n631\tin 2015 IEEE international conference on acoustics, speech and\n632\tsignal processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2015, pp. 5206–5210.\n633\t\n634\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "65640cb0-cbf8-4de6-ac0b-92e1229ec98a", "uuid": "dca34e10-009d-4da5-b748-58b00d2a2e59", "timestamp": "2026-07-06T13:56:31.274Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607.txt", "content": "An Efficient vLLM-Based Inference Pipeline for Unified Audio Understanding\nand Generation\nHaoran Wang1,2 , Jinchuan Tian1 , Siddhant Arora1 , Shinji Watanabe1,∗∗\n1\n2\n\nCarnegie Mellon University\nShanghai Jiao Tong University\nhaoranw5@andrew.cmu.edu\n\narXiv:2607.02119v1 [eess.AS] 2 Jul 2026\n\nAbstract\nWhile Large Multimodal Models excel in comprehension, highthroughput inference engines lack native support for multimodal generation. This is severe in Speech Language Models, where generating multi-layered audio tokens via decoupled\nAR+NAR or synchronous Multi-Token Prediction (MTP) with\ndelay-pattern interleaving conflicts with standard single-stream\nloops. We present a vLLM-based inference pipeline for unified\nspeech understanding and generation. We extend autoregressive decoding to natively execute delay-pattern de-interleaving\nand coordinated multi-stream sampling, integrating an on-GPU\nacoustic decoder for end-to-end waveform synthesis. Crucially,\nwe overcome the shared intuition that Classifier-Free Guidance\n(CFG) halves throughput. By co-scheduling paired conditional\nand unconditional requests within a continuous batch, our CFG\nimplementation sustains 80% of non-CFG throughput, absorbing dual-request and logit merging overheads. We open-source\nour framework1 .\nIndex Terms: Speech Language Models, High-Throughput Inference, End-to-End Speech Generation\n\n1. Introduction\nThe rapid evolution of Large Language Models (LLMs) has\ntransitioned artificial intelligence from text-only interfaces to\nrich, multimodal interactions. Recently, Speech Language\nModels (SpeechLMs) [1, 2, 3, 4] have emerged as a pivotal frontier for unified audio understanding and generation.\nBy modeling continuous audio signals as discrete acoustic tokens [5, 6, 7], these models bypass traditional cascaded Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) [8] and Text-to-Speech\n(TTS) [9, 10] pipelines to achieve strong and expressive acoustic capabilities. Building upon this end-to-end foundation, advanced interactive features like direct speech-to-speech dialogue [11, 12] naturally emerge as downstream applications.\nHowever, the deployment of SpeechLMs exposes a structural gap in current high-throughput inference engines. While\nstate-of-the-art serving frameworks [13, 14] excel at memory\nefficiency and dynamic request scheduling (e.g., continuous\nbatching [15] and automatic prefix caching [14]), their underlying mechanisms were largely optimized for unimodal, text-only\ngeneration. Consequently, extending this text-centric architecture to handle the continuous and distinct nature of speech outputs introduces significant bottlenecks.\nGenerating general audio diverges from standard text autoregression in two critical aspects:\n** indicates the corresponding author.\n1 https://github.com/whr-a/vllm/tree/opuslm\n\n1. Multi-Layered Token Generation and Decoding. Unlike\ntext, continuous speech is typically compressed by neural audio codecs [5, 7, 16, 17]. Modern SpeechLMs favor Residual\nVector Quantization (RVQ), encoding each temporal frame\ninto multi-layered tokens to support high-fidelity audio at\na constant frame rate. To model this multi-codebook grid,\ncurrent paradigms primarily adopt synchronous Multi-Token\nPrediction (MTP) [3] and delay-pattern interleaving [1, 18].\nWhile delay-pattern elegantly flattens tokens for training, its\ninference demands multi-stream sampling and complex deinterleaving. Furthermore, synthesizing the final waveform\nrequires an auxiliary acoustic decoder (vocoder). Coupling\nMTP with this additional decoding stage inherently conflicts\nwith the standard one-token-per-step serving loop.\n2. The Classifier-Free Guidance (CFG) Bottleneck.\nClassifier-Free Guidance (CFG) [19] is essential for highfidelity audio generation, as evidenced by its widespread\nadoption in various audio synthesis frameworks [18, 20, 21].\nMechanistically, implementing CFG requires two parallel\nforward passes per step: one conditioned on the input\nprompt and one unconditional. This dual-pass requirement\ninherently doubles computational and memory overheads.\nSince standard schedulers assume strict request independence, they lack native mechanisms to coordinate these\npaired passes. Consequently, naive implementations are\nforced to process them as separate requests. This disjoint\nscheduling duplicates KV cache allocations and precludes\njoint batching. Furthermore, the necessary logit merging\nmust operate across disjoint request contexts with explicit\nsynchronization. The compounding of these dual-request\noverheads and synchronization costs can severely degrade\noverall system throughput.\nTo bridge this gap, we present a novel inference implementation engineered for the unified understanding and generation\nof audio. Built upon vLLM [13] which is a high-performance\ncontinuous batching backend, our framework extends the autoregressive decoding loop to natively support synchronous\nmulti-stream sampling with delay-pattern de-interleaving for\nmulti-codebook audio generation. Furthermore, we fuse a\nlightweight acoustic decoder directly into the engine’s output\npipeline, enabling single-process audio synthesis without an external vocoder service\nTo address the CFG overhead, we introduce a Paired Request Co-Scheduling mechanism. By co-scheduling paired conditional and unconditional requests within the same continuous\nbatch, our approach ensures them to share a single forward pass\nthrough the transformer backbone. This unified execution elegantly absorbs the dual-request and logits merging overheads,\ndirectly overcoming the shared intuition that CFG inevitably\nhalves system throughput.\n\n\fCodebook token prediction head\n\nDelay Pattern\n-ccccc\n--cccc\n\n...\n\n...\n\n-----c\nDe-interleave\nAcoustic\nDecoder\n\nLLM Model Backbone\n\nAudio Encoder\n\nText Input\nText Output\nAudio Output\n\nAudio Input\n\nFigure 1: Speech language model architecture. The unified\nautoregressive transformer processes encoded audio and text.\nDuring audio generation, hidden states ht and stream embeddings ei (where 1 ≤ i ≤ S) are projected via S codebook\nheads into parallel delayed streams, which are subsequently deinterleaved for acoustic decoding.\nThe main contributions are summarized as follows.\n1. We identify the structural limitations of current text-centric\ninference engines in handling multimodal auto-regressive\ngeneration and propose a unified architecture that natively\nsupports synchronous multi-stream sampling and delaypattern de-interleaving for multi-codebook audio tokens.\n2. We design an end-to-end fused acoustic pipeline that integrates a lightweight audio decoder directly into the engine’s\noutput pipeline, eliminating the need for an external vocoder\nservice and enabling single-process waveform synthesis on\nGPU.\n3. We introduce a Paired Request Co-Scheduling strategy for\nCFG. By systematically pairing and co-scheduling conditional and unconditional requests within the same continuous\nbatch, our system efficiently absorbs dual-branch overheads\nand logit synchronization costs, sustaining up to 80% of nonCFG throughput and effectively overcoming the shared intuition of halved performance, while seamlessly supporting the\nconcurrent prefilling and decoding of text and CFG-enabled\naudio requests in a unified pipeline.\n\n2. Method\nWe present a serving framework that enables high-throughput\ninference for unified audio understanding and generation within\nexisting token-level continuous batching engines. We first describe the class of models our framework targets (§2.1), then\ndetail our unified serving pipeline (§2.3), and finally describe\nefficient Classifier-Free Guidance (§2.4).\n2.1. Speech Language Models\nOur system broadly targets the widely adopted delaypattern [18] SpeechLM architecture. To validate the generality\nof our pipeline, we ground our implementation and evaluation\nin three representative models: Bagpiper [1], OpusLM [2], and\nOpusLM dialogue [11]. As illustrated in Figure 1, the core generation mechanisms of these models share a unified architec-\n\ntural foundation.\nMulti-token Prediction. The pipeline begins with an audio\nencoder feeding continuous speech to an autoregressive LLM.\nThe LLM operates over a unified vocabulary, partitioned into\ntext and S audio sub-vocabulary. For audio output, at each time\nstep t, the LLM backbone produces a hidden state ht . As illustrated in Figure 1, S parallel codebook heads then project this\nstate to generate logits ℓ(i) and their corresponding sampled tokens ci (where 1 ≤ i ≤ S). Specifically, each head adds a\nlearnable stream embedding ei to ht before applying a shared\nlanguage modeling head WH , such that ℓ(i) = WH (ht + ei ).\nDelay Interleave pattern. Under the delay pattern [18],\nthe i-th stream is offset by i steps, meaning the S tokens\n{c1 , . . . , cS } emitted at step t correspond to different temporal\npositions. To maintain this structure during autoregressive feedback, the input representation at each step aggregates the embeddings of these previously generated tokens. Post-generation,\nthe resulting S × T codebook matrix (where T represents the\ntotal number of acoustic frames) is de-interleaved and passed to\nan acoustic decoder for waveform synthesis. Crucially, this unified vocabulary inherently enables mixed-modality responses\n(e.g., text seamlessly transitioning to audio).\n2.2. Standard Continuous Batching Engines\nModern text-based LLM serving frameworks, such as\nvLLM [13], maximize hardware utilization through iterationlevel scheduling and continuous batching. Rather than processing static batches where early-finishing requests idle, the\nscheduler dynamically injects new prompts and retires completed generations at the granularity of a single decoding step.\nThis highly dynamic scheduling is supported by memory management mechanisms like PagedAttention [13], which partitions the Key-Value (KV) cache into fixed-size, non-contiguous\nblocks to allocate GPU memory on demand and eliminate fragmentation. Structurally, these engines treat the underlying\nmodel as a black box that executes a uniform forward pass\nacross all active requests. Consequently, the entire system infrastructure is deeply coupled to the assumption of homogeneous, single-stream text generation, presenting a strict architectural constraint that our framework must navigate to support\nmulti-token prediction and CFG inference.\n2.3. Unified Multi-Token Prediction Serving Pipeline\nTo navigate this single-stream constraint and support S parallel audio tokens without requiring pervasive modifications to\nthe engine’s iteration-level scheduler or PagedAttention [13] infrastructure, we introduce a primary-auxiliary decomposition,\nas depicted in Figure 2 (Left).\nPrimary-Auxiliary Decomposition. We designate one\ncodebook stream as the primary token, which is fully managed\nby the engine’s standard pipeline. The remaining S−1 auxiliary\nstreams are sampled internally during the model’s logit computation and buffered per-request. Consequently, the model appears to the engine as a standard text LM that emits a single token per step, while transparently executing the multi-codebook\ngeneration.\nDe-interleave and Decode. Upon request completion, the\nbuffered matrix is delay-de-interleaved and passed to a colocated on-GPU acoustic decoder, fusing waveform synthesis\ndirectly into the serving path.\nMixed-Modality Phase Management. To orchestrate\nmixed text-audio outputs within this token-level engine, we implement a per-request phase state machine enforced via dy-\n\n\fText and/or\nRaw Audio\n\nRequest\n(CFG>1)\nauto-allocate\n\nServer\nScheduler\nMain\n(w/ cond)\n\nCompanion\n(w/o cond)\n\nModel\ntext\n\naudio\nDe-interleave\n\nAudio\nDecoder\n\nShared Forward\n(scheduled in the same batch)\n\nCFG Merge\nsample\n\nAssistant\nMessage\n\nMain Token\n\nCompanion\nSync Token\n\nNext step\n\nFigure 2: Unified serving framework for SpeechLMs. (Left)\nOverall pipeline: The engine manages continuous batching,\nprimary-auxiliary token generation, and fused on-GPU acoustic decoding for mixed-modality streaming. (Right) Paired coscheduling for CFG: Conditional and unconditional requests\nshare a batched forward pass, merging logits before sampling\nand synchronizing the sampled token for the next step.\nnamic vocabulary masking. The system transitions across three\nmain states: a text phase restricted to text tokens, a transition\nphase injecting deterministic bridging tokens to condition audio\ngeneration, and an audio phase activating all S streams. Crucially, terminating the audio phase initiates a drain sub-phase\nthat emits S−1 padding tokens to flush the delay buffer, guaranteeing a complete S × T codebook matrix (where T represents the total number of acoustic frames) for de-interleaving.\nFurthermore, because continuous batching interleaves tokens\nfrom multiple requests into a single flattened sequence, tracking modality via input positions is unreliable. We bypass this\nby dynamically inferring the active modality directly from the\nmodel’s unmasked output distribution (i.e., the argmax over\nthe disjoint vocabulary regions), ensuring robust and engineagnostic phase management.\n2.4. Classifier-Free Guidance via Paired Request CoScheduling\nClassifier-Free Guidance (CFG) [19] improves audio fidelity by\ninterpolating between conditional and unconditional distributions. Building upon the logit formulation ℓ(i) defined in Section 2.3, we apply CFG independently to each codebook stream\ni:\n(i)\n(i)\nℓ̃(i) = w · ℓcond + (1 − w) · ℓuncond , w > 1\n(1)\nA straightforward implementation would issue two independent requests, incurring severe scheduling fragmentation and\ncross-request synchronization overhead, and is not feasible because it needs step-by-step sync. To resolve this, we introduce\npaired request co-scheduling, which natively coordinates this\ndual-pass requirement within the serving engine.\nAs detailed in Figure 2 (Right), the end-to-end processing\npipeline begins with the input auto-allocation: when the server\nreceives a request with a CFG scale w > 1, it transparently generates a “Companion” request (with a null prompt) alongside\nthe “Main” conditional request. The engine treats this pair as an\natomic scheduling unit and always process them together. During the shared forward process, they are co-scheduled into the\n\nsame continuous batch and share a single forward pass through\nthe transformer backbone. The engine strictly partitions the perstep token budget equally between the pair.\n(i)\n(i)\nAfter the forward pass, the raw logits ℓcond and ℓuncond from\nboth contexts are merged according to Eq. 1. Crucially, this\nCFG merge operates only during the audio phase; it bypasses\nmodality-switching tokens to prevent CFG from corrupting the\nphase state machine. To avoid redundant compute, projections\nfor auxiliary streams are batched together.\nFinally, for the output and synchronization step, the engine\nsamples a single Main Token from the merged distribution ℓ̃(i) .\nTo ensure both contexts maintain the exact same autoregressive\nhistory for the next step, this sampled token is synchronously\nappended to the Companion request, while the companion’s external outputs remain hidden from the client. By systematically\nco-scheduling these pairs within the same continuous batch, our\narchitecture efficiently absorbs the dual-branch overheads and\nlogit synchronization costs. This design effectively overcomes\nthe conventional assumption that CFG halves performance, allowing the system to sustain up to 80% of non-CFG throughput.\n\n3. Experiment\n3.1. Experimental Setup\nWe evaluate our framework on three fully open-source\nSpeechLM architectures that span different design points, all\nsharing a delay-pattern codec structure and supporting both audio understanding and generation:\n• Bagpiper [1]: A model utilizing a Qwen3-8B [22] backbone\nwith 8 parallel codebook streams encoded via X-Codec [6].\nIt is designed for open-ended audio understanding and generation, natively supporting Classifier-Free Guidance for highfidelity audio synthesis.\n• OpusLM [2]: A model featuring an OLMo-2-7B [23] backbone with a 9-stream setup (1 SSL [24] + 8 DAC [5, 25]),\ntailored for both ASR and TTS tasks.\n• OpusLM-Dialogue [11]: A model adopting a SmolLM21.7B [26] backbone. It retains the same 9-stream codec configuration as OpusLM but is specifically optimized for spoken\ndialogue tasks.\nFor the baseline, we use the original PyTorch inference\npipeline, which processes requests sequentially without continuous batching. All experiments are conducted on a single\nNVIDIA H100 80GB GPU with FlashAttention-3 [27] enabled.\nThe maximum model sequence length is set to 16,384 tokens for\nall configurations. To maximize operational efficiency and fully\nsaturate the GPU, we maintain a concurrency level of 512 simultaneous requests for standard evaluations. For CFG-enabled\nsettings, the concurrency is proportionally adjusted to 256 requests to account for the internal companion requests, yielding an equivalent active workload. This targeted concurrency\nensures that the serving engine maintains a steady, moderately\nsized queue to sustain peak overall throughput.\n3.2. Throughput\nIn addition to decode token rates, we measure Model FLOPs\nUtilization (MFU), which quantifies the ratio of actual floatingpoint operations to the GPU’s theoretical peak capacity, providing a standardized metric for hardware utility. As summarized in Table 1, our continuous-batching pipeline achieves\nmassive performance gains over the sequential PyTorch baseline across all models. By effectively batching multi-stream\ngeneration, our system accelerates token processing speeds by\n\n\fTable 1: Prompt and generation throughput comparison. All\nmeasurements are conducted on a single H100 80GB GPU with\nFlashAttention-3 and a maximum sequence length of 16,384.\nSystem\n\nDecode (tok/s) MFU (%)\n\nBagpiper (PyTorch)\nBagpiper (vLLM)\n\n52.7\n5694.5\n\nTable 3: Inference quality evaluation. Understanding is measured by MMAU-mini accuracy (%, ↑) and ASR word error rate\n(%, ↓). Generation is measured by TTS word error rate (%, ↓)\nand dialogue UTMOS (↑). “–” indicates the task is not supported by the model.\n\n0.096\n9.95\n\nUnderstanding\nMMAU↑\n-mini\n\nASR↓\n\nTTS↓\n\nUTMOS↑\n\nBagpiper (PyTorch)\nBagpiper (vLLM)\n\n74.5\n75.4\n\n2.5\n2.6\n\n2.7\n3.3\n\n–\n–\n\nOpusLM (PyTorch)\nOpusLM (vLLM)\n\n–\n–\n\n2.3\n1.9\n\n4.6\n5.3\n\n–\n–\n\nOpusLM-Dial. (PyTorch)\nOpusLM-Dial. (vLLM)\n\n–\n–\n\n–\n–\n\n–\n–\n\n2.85\n2.51\n\nOpusLM (PyTorch)\nOpusLM (vLLM)\n\n36.5\n4582.9\n\n0.311\n9.89\n\nOpusLM-Dial. (PyTorch)\nOpusLM-Dial. (vLLM)\n\n53.9\n5870.5\n\n0.290\n3.28\n\nroughly two orders of magnitude. This architectural advantage\ndirectly translates to hardware utilization: while the baseline\nseverely underutilizes the H100 GPU with an MFU well below\n0.1%, our serving engine efficiently absorbs scheduling overheads to drive the MFU up to 9.95% for Bagpiper and 9.89%\nfor OpusLM. Notably, the 1.7B parameter OpusLM dialogue\nmodel exhibits a lower MFU of 3.28% despite achieving the\nhighest absolute token throughput. This occurs because such a\ncompact model possesses low arithmetic intensity on the H100\nGPU, causing inference to hit the memory bandwidth wall before fully saturating the compute units.\n3.3. Numerical and Quality Check\nA prerequisite for any serving optimization is that it must not\ndegrade model output quality. We verify numerical correctness\nusing the Bagpiper model [1] on the MMAU-mini dataset [28].\nSpecifically, we compare the token sequences and logit distributions produced by our continuous-batching pipeline against the\nreference PyTorch implementation under identical inputs and\nrandom seeds.\nTable 2: Numerical deviation against the reference PyTorch implementation.\nConfiguration\n\nRMSE\n(Max)\n\nRMSE\n(Mean)\n\nFirst\nMismatch\n\nFP32 + SDPA [29]\nBF16 + FA3 [27]\n\n0.081\n0.532\n\n0.008\n0.163\n\nNone (Identical)\n34.0\n\nAs shown in Table 2, under Float32 precision, the two implementations produce strictly identical token sequences, with\na negligible mean logit RMSE of 0.008. This exact alignment\nconfirms that our custom multi-stream sampling and phase control introduce no numerical bugs. When transitioning to BF16\nwith FlashAttention-3 [27], a mismatch occurs around step\n34, increasing the mean RMSE to 0.163. This discrepancy is\nan expected consequence of precision loss and non-associative\nfloating-point arithmetic [30, 31].\nCrucially, this inherent hardware-level divergence does not\nnegatively impact end-to-end model fidelity. To confirm this\nempirically, we evaluate inference quality across understanding and generation tasks, as summarized in Table 3. We report\naccuracy on MMAU-mini [28] and word error rate (WER) on\nLibriSpeech test-clean [32] for understanding. For generation,\nwe report WER on LibriSpeech test-clean and UTMOS on the\nEval2000 dataset. While minor instance-level variations in synthesized speech naturally arise from hardware precision shifts\nand the inherent variance of TTS generation, outputs produced\nby our pipeline safely maintain the expected aggregate performance of the underlying models across all metrics.\n\nSystem\n\nGeneration\n\nTable 4: CFG overhead on Bagpiper (vLLM). Prompt and\ngeneration throughput (tok/s) and MFU (%) with and without\nClassifier-Free Guidance.\nSetting\n\nPrefill (tok/s)\n\nDecode (tok/s)\n\nMFU (%)\n\nw/o CFG\nw/ CFG\n\n315.8\n271.2\n\n4952.0\n3960.7\n\n8.0\n12.8\n\n3.4. CFG Overhead Analysis\nWhile CFG inherently doubles compute via parallel forward\npasses, Table 4 shows our co-scheduling sustains over 80% of\nbaseline throughput. These measurements are conducted using\nBagpiper on the LibriSpeech TTS task, operating at concurrencies of 256 and 512 for the CFG and baseline configurations,\nrespectively. This efficiency stems from three factors. First,\nthe companion request strictly copies the main sequence, ensuring near-perfect prefix cache hits and minimizing KV cache\noverhead. Second, since autoregressive decoding is fundamentally memory-bound, processing the companion request merely\nconstitutes a marginal addition to the active batch size. This\nsaturates idle compute to boost MFU with negligible latency\nand synchronization penalties. Finally, models like Bagpiper\ngenerate extensive textual reasoning before brief audio outputs.\nSelectively activating CFG solely during this short audio phase\neffectively amortizes the dual-pass cost across the entire end-toend sequence.\n\n4. Conclusion\nIn this work, we presented a unified inference architecture\nthat extends a continuous batching engine to natively support\nSpeech Language Models. By integrating synchronous multistream sampling and delay-pattern de-interleaving into the generation loop, our design effectively handles the complexities\nof multi-layered audio tokens. Through a Paired Request CoScheduling strategy, our system efficiently absorbs dual-branch\noverheads, sustaining 80% of non-CFG throughput. Experimental results across multiple SpeechLM architectures demonstrate up to 108× generation throughput improvement over sequential PyTorch inference while maintaining strict numerical correctness. As the modifications remain confined to the\nmodel and logit processing layers, this architecture provides a\nportable and high-performance foundation for real-time multimodal voice applications.\n\n\f5. Generative AI Use Disclosure\nArtificial intelligence tools were utilized exclusively for language editing and manuscript polishing. The core technical\ncontributions, including the system architecture design, framework implementation, and experimental evaluation, were independently conducted by the authors.\n\n6. Acknowledgment\nThis work used the Bridges2 at PSC and Delta/DeltaAI NCSA\nsystems through CIS210014 from the ACCESS program, supported by NSF #2138259, #2138286, #2138307, #2137603, and\n#2138296.\n\n7. References\n[1] J. Tian, H. Wang, B.-H. Su, C.-y. Huang, Q. Wang, J. Shi,\nW. Chen, X. Gong, S. Arora, C.-J. Li et al., “Bagpiper: Solving open-ended audio tasks via rich captions,” arXiv preprint\narXiv:2602.05220, 2026.\n[2] J. Tian, W. Chen, Y. Peng, J. Shi, S. Arora, S. Bharadwaj,\nT. Maekaku, Y. Shinohara, K. Goto, X. Yue et al., “Opuslm: A\nfamily of open unified speech language models,” arXiv preprint\narXiv:2506.17611, 2025.\n[3] J. Xu, Z. Guo, H. Hu, Y. Chu, X. Wang, J. He, Y. Wang,\nX. Shi, T. He, X. Zhu et al., “Qwen3-omni technical report,” arXiv\npreprint arXiv:2509.17765, 2025.\n[4] D. Ding, Z. Ju, Y. Leng, S. Liu, T. Liu, Z. Shang, K. Shen,\nW. Song, X. Tan, H. Tang et al., “Kimi-audio technical report,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2504.18425, 2025.\n[5] J. Shi, J. Tian, Y. Wu, J.-w. Jung, J. Q. Yip, Y. Masuyama,\nW. Chen, Y. Wu, Y. Tang, M. Baali et al., “Espnet-codec: Comprehensive training and evaluation of neural codecs for audio, music,\nand speech,” in 2024 IEEE Spoken language technology workshop\n(SLT). IEEE, 2024, pp. 562–569.\n[6] Z. Ye, P. Sun, J. Lei, H. Lin, X. Tan, Z. Dai, Q. Kong, J. Chen,\nJ. Pan, Q. Liu et al., “Codec does matter: Exploring the semantic\nshortcoming of codec for audio language model,” in Proceedings\nof the AAAI Conference on Artificial Intelligence, vol. 39, no. 24,\n2025, pp. 25 697–25 705.\n[7] H. Wang, J. Shi, J. Tian, B. Li, K. Yu, and S. Watanabe, “Bscodec:\nA band-split neural codec for high-quality universal audio reconstruction,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2511.06150, 2025.\n[8] A. Radford, J. W. Kim, T. Xu, G. Brockman, C. McLeavey, and\nI. Sutskever, “Robust speech recognition via large-scale weak\nsupervision,” in International conference on machine learning.\nPMLR, 2023, pp. 28 492–28 518.\n\n[13] W. Kwon, Z. Li, S. Zhuang, Y. Sheng, L. Zheng, C. H. Yu, J. E.\nGonzalez, H. Zhang, and I. Stoica, “Efficient memory management for large language model serving with pagedattention,” in\nProceedings of the ACM SIGOPS 29th Symposium on Operating\nSystems Principles, 2023.\n[14] L. Zheng, L. Yin, Z. Xie, C. L. Sun, J. Huang, C. H. Yu, S. Cao,\nC. Kozyrakis, I. Stoica, J. E. Gonzalez et al., “Sglang: Efficient\nexecution of structured language model programs,” Advances\nin neural information processing systems, vol. 37, pp. 62 557–\n62 583, 2024.\n[15] G.-I. Yu, J. S. Jeong, G.-W. Kim, S. Kim, and B.-G. Chun, “Orca:\nA distributed serving system for {Transformer-Based} generative\nmodels,” in 16th USENIX symposium on operating systems design\nand implementation (OSDI 22), 2022, pp. 521–538.\n[16] P. Mousavi, G. Maimon, A. Moumen, D. Petermann, J. Shi,\nH. Wu, H. Yang, A. Kuznetsova, A. Ploujnikov, R. Marxer et al.,\n“Discrete audio tokens: More than a survey!” arXiv preprint\narXiv:2506.10274, 2025.\n[17] Y. Guo, Z. Li, H. Wang, B. Li, C. Shao, H. Zhang, C. Du, X. Chen,\nS. Liu, and K. Yu, “Recent advances in discrete speech tokens:\nA review,” IEEE Transactions on Pattern Analysis and Machine\nIntelligence, 2025.\n[18] J. Copet, F. Kreuk, I. Gat, T. Remez, D. Kant, G. Synnaeve,\nY. Adi, and A. Défossez, “Simple and controllable music generation,” Advances in neural information processing systems, vol. 36,\npp. 47 704–47 720, 2023.\n[19] J. Ho and T. Salimans, “Classifier-free diffusion guidance,” arXiv\npreprint arXiv:2207.12598, 2022.\n[20] J. Tian, S.-g. Lee, Z. Kong, S. Ghosh, A. Goel, C.-H. H. Yang,\nW. Dai, Z. Liu, H. Ye, S. Watanabe et al., “Ualm: Unified audio language model for understanding, generation and reasoning,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2510.12000, 2025.\n[21] H. Liu, Z. Chen, Y. Yuan, X. Mei, X. Liu, D. Mandic, W. Wang,\nand M. D. Plumbley, “Audioldm: Text-to-audio generation with\nlatent diffusion models,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2301.12503, 2023.\n[22] A. Yang, A. Li, B. Yang, B. Zhang, B. Hui, B. Zheng, B. Yu,\nC. Gao, C. Huang, C. Lv et al., “Qwen3 technical report,” arXiv\npreprint arXiv:2505.09388, 2025.\n[23] T. OLMo, P. Walsh, L. Soldaini, D. Groeneveld, K. Lo, S. Arora,\nA. Bhagia, Y. Gu, S. Huang, M. Jordan et al., “2 olmo 2 furious,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2501.00656, 2024.\n[24] W. Chen, W. Zhang, Y. Peng, X. Li, J. Tian, J. Shi, X. Chang,\nS. Maiti, K. Livescu, and S. Watanabe, “Towards robust speech\nrepresentation learning for thousands of languages,” in Proceedings of the 2024 Conference on Empirical Methods in Natural\nLanguage Processing, 2024, pp. 10 205–10 224.\n[25] R. Kumar, P. Seetharaman, A. Luebs, I. Kumar, and K. Kumar,\n“High-fidelity audio compression with improved rvqgan,” Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems, vol. 36, pp.\n27 980–27 993, 2023.\n\n[9] J. Kim, J. Kong, and J. Son, “Conditional variational autoencoder\nwith adversarial learning for end-to-end text-to-speech,” in International conference on machine learning.\nPMLR, 2021, pp.\n5530–5540.\n\n[26] L. B. Allal, A. Lozhkov, E. Bakouch, G. M. Blázquez, G. Penedo,\nL. Tunstall, A. Marafioti, H. Kydlı́ček, A. P. Lajarı́n, V. Srivastav\net al., “Smollm2: When smol goes big–data-centric training of a\nsmall language model,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2502.02737, 2025.\n\n[10] J. Shen, R. Pang, R. J. Weiss, M. Schuster, N. Jaitly, Z. Yang,\nZ. Chen, Y. Zhang, Y. Wang, R. Skerrv-Ryan et al., “Natural\ntts synthesis by conditioning wavenet on mel spectrogram predictions,” in 2018 IEEE international conference on acoustics,\nspeech and signal processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2018, pp. 4779–\n4783.\n\n[27] J. Shah, G. Bikshandi, Y. Zhang, V. Thakkar, P. Ramani, and\nT. Dao, “Flashattention-3: Fast and accurate attention with asynchrony and low-precision,” Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems, vol. 37, pp. 68 658–68 685, 2024.\n\n[11] S. Arora, J. Tian, J. Shi, H. Futami, Y. Kashiwagi, E. Tsunoo,\nand S. Watanabe, “Optimizing conversational quality in spoken\ndialogue systems with reinforcement learning from ai feedback,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2601.19063, 2026.\n[12] A. Défossez, L. Mazaré, M. Orsini, A. Royer, P. Pérez, H. Jégou,\nE. Grave, and N. Zeghidour, “Moshi: a speech-text foundation\nmodel for real-time dialogue,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2410.00037,\n2024.\n\n[28] S. Sakshi, U. Tyagi, S. Kumar, A. Seth, R. Selvakumar, O. Nieto,\nR. Duraiswami, S. Ghosh, and D. Manocha, “Mmau: A massive\nmulti-task audio understanding and reasoning benchmark,” arXiv\npreprint arXiv:2410.19168, 2024.\n[29] A. Vaswani, N. Shazeer, N. Parmar, J. Uszkoreit, L. Jones, A. N.\nGomez, Ł. Kaiser, and I. Polosukhin, “Attention is all you need,”\nAdvances in neural information processing systems, vol. 30, 2017.\n[30] A. Golden, S. Hsia, F. Sun, B. Acun, B. Hosmer, Y. Lee, Z. DeVito, J. Johnson, G.-Y. Wei, D. Brooks et al., “Is flash attention\nstable?” arXiv preprint arXiv:2405.02803, 2024.\n\n\f[31] J. Yuan, H. Li, X. Ding, W. Xie, Y.-J. Li, W. Zhao, K. Wan,\nJ. Shi, X. Hu, and Z. Liu, “Understanding and mitigating numerical sources of nondeterminism in llm inference,” arXiv preprint\narXiv:2506.09501, 2025.\n[32] V. Panayotov, G. Chen, D. Povey, and S. Khudanpur, “Librispeech: an asr corpus based on public domain audio books,”\nin 2015 IEEE international conference on acoustics, speech and\nsignal processing (ICASSP). IEEE, 2015, pp. 5206–5210.\n\n\f", "numLines": 634, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 634}}}
