{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a782e6f6c67740d4", "type": "tool_result", "content": "=== paper: 2602.05220 ===\nPaper 2602.05220 not found\n=== paper: 2506.17611 ===\nPaper 2506.17611 not found\n=== paper: 2509.17765 ===\n# Qwen3-Omni Technical Report\narXiv: 2509.17765\nAuthors: Jin Xu, Zhifang Guo, Hangrui Hu, Yunfei Chu, Xiong Wang, Jinzheng He, Yuxuan Wang, Xian Shi, Ting He, Xinfa Zhu, Yuanjun Lv, Yongqi Wang, Dake Guo, He Wang, Linhan Ma, Pei Zhang, Xinyu Zhang, Hongkun Hao, Zishan Guo, Baosong Yang, Bin Zhang, Ziyang Ma, Xipin Wei, Shuai Bai, Keqin Chen, Xuejing Liu, Peng Wang, Mingkun Yang, Dayiheng Liu, Xingzhang Ren, Bo Zheng, Rui Men, Fan Zhou, Bowen Yu, Jianxin Yang, Le Yu, Jingren Zhou, Junyang Lin\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Qwen3-Omni is the first single multimodal model to maintain state-of-the-art performance across text, image, audio, and video without degradation relative to single-modal counterparts.\n  2. The model adopts a Thinker-Talker Mixture-of-Experts architecture that unifies perception and generation across text, images, audio, and video to yield fluent text and natural real-time speech.\n  3. It replaces the Whisper audio encoder with an Audio Transformer encoder trained from scratch on 20 million hours of supervised audio to yield stronger general-purpose audio representations.\n  4. A multi-codebook autoregressive scheme with a multi-token prediction module is introduced for speech generation, replacing block-wise diffusion with a lightweight causal ConvNet.\n  5. The system supports text interaction in 119 languages, speech understanding in 19 languages, and speech generation in 10 languages.\n  6. A Time-aligned Multimodal Rotary Position Embedding interleaves rotary angles across temporal, height, and width dimensions to enhance long-range dependency modeling for multimodal streams.\n  7. A Thinking model is introduced to explicitly reason over inputs from any modality, including audio-video and audio-only scenarios.\n  8. Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Captioner is fine-tuned to produce detailed, low-hallucination captions for arbitrary audio inputs to address the lack of general-purpose audio captioning models.\n  9. The model achieves a theoretical end-to-end first-packet latency of 234 ms in cold-start settings through chunked prefilling and streaming multi-codebook codec generation.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/对话型, LALM/潜在表示, LALM/对话型-并行生成, TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/功能-流式\n=== paper: 2504.18425 ===\n# Kimi-Audio Technical Report\narXiv: 2504.18425\nAuthors: KimiTeam, Ding Ding, Zeqian Ju, Yichong Leng, Songxiang Liu, Tong Liu, Zeyu Shang, Kai Shen, Wei Song, Xu Tan, Heyi Tang, Zhengtao Wang, Chu Wei, Yifei Xin, Xinran Xu, Jianwei Yu, Yutao Zhang, Xinyu Zhou, Y. Charles, Jun Chen, Yanru Chen, Yulun Du, Weiran He, Zhenxing Hu, Guokun Lai, Qingcheng Li, Yangyang Liu, Weidong Sun, Jianzhou Wang, Yuzhi Wang, Yuefeng Wu, Yuxin Wu, Dongchao Yang, Hao Yang, Ying Yang, Zhilin Yang, Aoxiong Yin, Ruibin Yuan, Yutong Zhang, Zaida Zhou\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of a universal, open-source audio foundation model (Kimi-Audio) that achieves state-of-the-art performance across audio understanding, generation, and speech conversation tasks within a single unified framework.\n  2. Design of a novel LLM architecture featuring continuous acoustic features as input and discrete semantic tokens as output, utilizing shared transformer layers with parallel dual-generation heads for text and audio.\n  3. Development of a chunk-wise streaming detokenizer based on flow matching, incorporating a training-free look-ahead mechanism to generate high-quality and low-latency audio waveforms.\n  4. Curation of a large-scale pre-training dataset comprising over 13 million hours of diverse audio data, processed via an automatic pipeline to generate high-quality, long-form annotations.\n  5. Construction of a cost-effective, diverse supervised fine-tuning dataset entirely from open-source data and processing tools, without relying on data purchases.\n  6. Design of a comprehensive continual pre-training strategy that initializes from a pre-trained text LLM and bridges the audio-text gap through unimodal, mapping, and interleaving pre-training tasks.\n  7. Creation and open-sourcing of a standardized evaluation toolkit that ensures fair and reproducible benchmarking of audio foundation models across diverse tasks.\n\nTags: LALM, TTS, LALM/对话型, LALM/理解型, LALM/音频标记-融合, TTS/功能-流式, LALM/对话型-并行生成\n=== paper: 2410.00037 ===\n# Moshi: a speech-text foundation model for real-time dialogue\narXiv: 2410.00037\nAuthors: Alexandre Défossez, Laurent Mazaré, Manu Orsini, Amélie Royer, Patrick Pérez, Hervé Jégou, Edouard Grave, Neil Zeghidour\nYear: 2024 | Venue: \nTopic: dialogue_system\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We present Helium, a 7B-parameter text LLM pre-trained on 2.1T tokens of filtered public English data.\n  2. We train Mimi, a neural audio codec that distills semantic information into the first level of acoustic tokens using a split residual vector quantizer.\n  3. We propose a new hierarchical, streaming architecture for audio language modeling that extends the RQ-Transformer with per-codebook parameters and acoustic delays to jointly generate semantic and acoustic tokens.\n  4. We introduce a multi-stream audio language model architecture that explicitly processes the input and output audio streams in parallel to handle full-duplex dialogues with arbitrary conversational dynamics.\n  5. We introduce Inner Monologue, a training and inference method that predicts time-aligned text tokens as a prefix to audio tokens to significantly improve the linguistic quality of generated speech while remaining compatible with streaming inference.\n  6. We demonstrate that adjusting the delay between text and audio tokens within the Inner Monologue framework allows a single model to function as both a streaming ASR and a streaming TTS system.\n\nTags: LALM, 压缩, TTS, LALM/对话型, LALM/音频标记-融合, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-混合, TTS/功能-流式", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "65640cb0-cbf8-4de6-ac0b-92e1229ec98a", "uuid": "39e90188-ead5-4fe7-aca9-bd130f7b18ce", "timestamp": "2026-07-06T13:57:19.247Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "=== paper: 2602.05220 ===\nPaper 2602.05220 not found\n=== paper: 2506.17611 ===\nPaper 2506.17611 not found\n=== paper: 2509.17765 ===\n# Qwen3-Omni Technical Report\narXiv: 2509.17765\nAuthors: Jin Xu, Zhifang Guo, Hangrui Hu, Yunfei Chu, Xiong Wang, Jinzheng He, Yuxuan Wang, Xian Shi, Ting He, Xinfa Zhu, Yuanjun Lv, Yongqi Wang, Dake Guo, He Wang, Linhan Ma, Pei Zhang, Xinyu Zhang, Hongkun Hao, Zishan Guo, Baosong Yang, Bin Zhang, Ziyang Ma, Xipin Wei, Shuai Bai, Keqin Chen, Xuejing Liu, Peng Wang, Mingkun Yang, Dayiheng Liu, Xingzhang Ren, Bo Zheng, Rui Men, Fan Zhou, Bowen Yu, Jianxin Yang, Le Yu, Jingren Zhou, Junyang Lin\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Qwen3-Omni is the first single multimodal model to maintain state-of-the-art performance across text, image, audio, and video without degradation relative to single-modal counterparts.\n  2. The model adopts a Thinker-Talker Mixture-of-Experts architecture that unifies perception and generation across text, images, audio, and video to yield fluent text and natural real-time speech.\n  3. It replaces the Whisper audio encoder with an Audio Transformer encoder trained from scratch on 20 million hours of supervised audio to yield stronger general-purpose audio representations.\n  4. A multi-codebook autoregressive scheme with a multi-token prediction module is introduced for speech generation, replacing block-wise diffusion with a lightweight causal ConvNet.\n  5. The system supports text interaction in 119 languages, speech understanding in 19 languages, and speech generation in 10 languages.\n  6. A Time-aligned Multimodal Rotary Position Embedding interleaves rotary angles across temporal, height, and width dimensions to enhance long-range dependency modeling for multimodal streams.\n  7. A Thinking model is introduced to explicitly reason over inputs from any modality, including audio-video and audio-only scenarios.\n  8. Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Captioner is fine-tuned to produce detailed, low-hallucination captions for arbitrary audio inputs to address the lack of general-purpose audio captioning models.\n  9. The model achieves a theoretical end-to-end first-packet latency of 234 ms in cold-start settings through chunked prefilling and streaming multi-codebook codec generation.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/对话型, LALM/潜在表示, LALM/对话型-并行生成, TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/功能-流式\n=== paper: 2504.18425 ===\n# Kimi-Audio Technical Report\narXiv: 2504.18425\nAuthors: KimiTeam, Ding Ding, Zeqian Ju, Yichong Leng, Songxiang Liu, Tong Liu, Zeyu Shang, Kai Shen, Wei Song, Xu Tan, Heyi Tang, Zhengtao Wang, Chu Wei, Yifei Xin, Xinran Xu, Jianwei Yu, Yutao Zhang, Xinyu Zhou, Y. Charles, Jun Chen, Yanru Chen, Yulun Du, Weiran He, Zhenxing Hu, Guokun Lai, Qingcheng Li, Yangyang Liu, Weidong Sun, Jianzhou Wang, Yuzhi Wang, Yuefeng Wu, Yuxin Wu, Dongchao Yang, Hao Yang, Ying Yang, Zhilin Yang, Aoxiong Yin, Ruibin Yuan, Yutong Zhang, Zaida Zhou\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of a universal, open-source audio foundation model (Kimi-Audio) that achieves state-of-the-art performance across audio understanding, generation, and speech conversation tasks within a single unified framework.\n  2. Design of a novel LLM architecture featuring continuous acoustic features as input and discrete semantic tokens as output, utilizing shared transformer layers with parallel dual-generation heads for text and audio.\n  3. Development of a chunk-wise streaming detokenizer base